\f1\b \cf0 \strokec3 1st review\
EquityRoots \'97 What Actually Works, What Doesn't\
\pard\tx26756\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The uncomfortable truth first:
\f0\b0  This site will help you 
\f2\i filter and rank
\f0\i0 , but you cannot make a final buy/sell decision here. It's a shortlisting tool, not a research terminal. If you're treating a score of 80 as a buy signal, you're misusing it.\
\pard\tx28280\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\tx26756\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \strokec3 What's Genuinely Good\
\pard\tx26756\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Peer-relative scoring is the real insight here.
\f0\b0  Most retail investors compare a small-cap NBFC's P/E to HDFC Bank's and draw wrong conclusions. EquityRoots' core idea \'97 score stocks only within their peer cluster and maturity tier \'97 is analytically sound and underused in free Indian tools.\
The three pillars (Quality, Valuation, Momentum) with sector-specific recipes are well thought-out. Banks being scored on RoA and CASA instead of P/E, cement on EBITDA/capacity instead of earnings \'97 this is how analysts actually think. The glossary is exceptional: real Indian company examples, not just formula definitions.\
The screener is clean and the CSV export is useful. Ideas feed (compounders, cheap-in-cluster, FII/promoter accumulation) gives a structured starting point.\
\pard\tx26756\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\tx26756\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \strokec3 Critical Gaps That Hurt Decision-Making\
\pard\tx26756\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1. No forward-looking data.
\f0\b0  There are zero analyst estimates, no EPS forecasts, no forward P/E. You're flying entirely on trailing numbers. A stock that looks cheap on TTM P/E may have just had its best-ever quarter. You'd never know here.\

\f1\b 2. No price charts or technical view.
\f0\b0  [Likely] A significant portion of retail entry/exit decisions involve moving averages, support/resistance, volume patterns. Nothing here. You'd still need Tradingview or Chartink before acting.\

\f1\b 3. Opaque scoring weights.
\f0\b0  The specific pillar weights are "research IP." This is a legitimate trust problem. A 80 score tells you the stock ranks well, but you can't verify 
\f2\i why
\f0\i0  \'97 the scoring can mask a single strong factor hiding two weak ones. The Q/V/M split helps partially, but it's not enough.\

\f1\b 4. Only 9 weeks of historical snapshots.
\f0\b0  You can't see whether a stock's quality score has been trending up for 2 years or just jumped last week. Trend matters more than level.\

\f1\b 5. No BSE coverage.
\f0\b0  Only NSE stocks. BSE has thousands of additional companies including SME listings that many retail investors actively trade.\

\f1\b 6. No portfolio or watchlist feature.
\f0\b0  You can't save a list of stocks, track their score changes over time, or get alerted when a stock you're watching crosses a threshold. Every visit starts from scratch.\

\f1\b 7. Weekly cadence is too slow for events.
\f0\b0  If a company announces a profit warning on Tuesday, the score won't reflect it until Friday. Earnings season makes this a real gap.\

\f1\b 8. Relative scoring can be misleading in bad sectors.
\f0\b0  A score of 75 in a sector where all companies are mediocre is not the same as 75 in a strong sector. The site acknowledges this but doesn't solve it. There's no absolute quality floor signal \'97 a stock can rank 1st of 12 in a terrible industry.\
\pard\tx26756\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\tx26756\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

